At ambient temperature, the charge transport in organic solar cells is likely to occur through the thermally activated hopping model. In this model, the charge carriers localize on a single molecule and hop from one molecule to the adjacent molecule. The charge transfer rate constant (k) between equivalent neighbouring molecules can be defined by semiclassical Marcus theory. The charge transfer rate constant can be expressed as follows (the free energy difference (ΔG) for the self-exchange CT reaction process is neglected)52,65,66.6k=2πħV214πλkBTexp-λ4kBT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
